1
00:00:16,566 --> 00:00:18,955


2
00:00:19,603 --> 00:00:21,901


3
00:00:22,606 --> 00:00:24,870


4
00:00:25,309 --> 00:00:27,573


5
00:00:54,675 --> 00:00:58,275


6
00:00:58,876 --> 00:01:04,276


7
00:03:48,577 --> 00:03:54,077


8
00:03:54,585 --> 00:03:56,077
I hope our new Commander-in-Chief...

9
00:03:56,186 --> 00:03:58,643
isn't the coward they say he is.

10
00:03:58,822 --> 00:04:00,084
Whatever they say,

11
00:04:00,290 --> 00:04:01,120
Yamamoto is the kind of leader we need.

12
00:04:03,260 --> 00:04:05,387
He believes in the value of the airplane.

13
00:04:06,062 --> 00:04:08,826
But why a Vice-Navy Minister...

14
00:04:08,999 --> 00:04:10,159
for such an important position?

15
00:04:10,467 --> 00:04:13,595
Maybe the climate in Tokyo was detrimental to Yamamoto's health.

16
00:04:13,868 --> 00:04:16,428
The Army is against him...

17
00:04:16,903 --> 00:04:18,173
for opposing their policies.

18
00:04:18,441 --> 00:04:19,231
So he runs away to sea.

19
00:04:20,644 --> 00:04:26,241
Now he has the entire fleet to guard him.

20
00:05:02,223 --> 00:05:08,223


21
00:05:08,224 --> 00:05:11,887


22
00:05:58,391 --> 00:06:01,991


23
00:06:48,392 --> 00:06:51,781
This order makes you Commander-in-Chief.

24
00:06:51,928 --> 00:06:54,165
The Imperial fleet consists of--

25
00:06:54,165 --> 00:06:57,120
Save your breath, Yoshida.

26
00:06:57,266 --> 00:06:59,462
Those details are in the documents.

27
00:06:59,702 --> 00:07:01,192
You haven't changed!

28
00:07:03,473 --> 00:07:05,270
With the Army controlling politics...

29
00:07:05,842 --> 00:07:08,037
...your job as Navy Minister will be difficult.

30
00:07:08,111 --> 00:07:09,100
Don't mess it up

31
00:07:09,779 --> 00:07:11,440
Thank God you're here.

32
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:13,873
We know your life has been threatened.

33
00:07:15,017 --> 00:07:17,519
I'm not that easy to kill.

34
00:07:20,056 --> 00:07:22,286
Army hotheads are demanding

35
00:07:22,492 --> 00:07:25,381
an alliance with Germany.

36
00:07:26,863 --> 00:07:28,626
That would be tragic for Japan.

37
00:07:29,165 --> 00:07:34,831
As Navy Minister l will continue to fight with the Army.

38
00:07:36,506 --> 00:07:38,997
You are our last hope, Yoshida.

39
00:07:40,143 --> 00:07:42,941
The Navy must stand firm against the alliance.

40
00:07:50,090 --> 00:07:54,390


41
00:07:55,491 --> 00:07:58,915
America is against the war we are waging in China...

42
00:07:59,312 --> 00:08:02,647
...and angry that we are negotiating with the Germans.

43
00:08:03,366 --> 00:08:08,394
Now we are threatened with an embargo of the raw materials we need.

44
00:08:09,238 --> 00:08:11,934
Either we improve relations with the U.S. ...

45
00:08:12,141 --> 00:08:16,505
and withdraw from China

46
00:08:17,046 --> 00:08:22,208
...or find another source of raw materials here in Indo-China.

47
00:08:22,885 --> 00:08:25,740
Why worry about threats from America?

48
00:08:26,889 --> 00:08:30,222
President Roosevelt's attention is on Europe...

49
00:08:30,893 --> 00:08:32,884
...where Germany is winning a quick victory over the Allied Armies.

50
00:08:33,096 --> 00:08:34,393
So I think we don't have to withdraw our force...

51
00:08:34,464 --> 00:08:35,658
from China

52
00:08:36,559 --> 00:08:39,659


53
00:08:40,069 --> 00:08:42,196
Now is the time to strike.

54
00:08:43,272 --> 00:08:49,268
The British, the Dutch and the French are withdrawing their forces...

55
00:08:50,613 --> 00:08:52,478
...from Southeast Asia ...

56
00:08:52,682 --> 00:08:57,210
to strengthen their armies in Europe.

57
00:08:58,421 --> 00:09:01,379
We must be careful.

58
00:09:02,658 --> 00:09:08,382
The Americans have an Army in the Philippines...

59
00:09:08,633 --> 00:09:11,222
...and they have moved ...

60
00:09:11,300 --> 00:09:16,127
their Pacific Fleet from San Diego to Pearl Harbor

61
00:09:18,977 --> 00:09:24,704
Yes, and that fleet is a knife leveled at Japan's throat.

62
00:09:26,005 --> 00:09:29,005


63
00:09:31,006 --> 00:09:38,806


64
00:09:46,907 --> 00:09:50,207


65
00:09:56,007 --> 00:09:58,107


66
00:10:06,722 --> 00:10:10,112
The Japanese ambassador just arrived. He should be up shortly.

67
00:10:10,860 --> 00:10:11,758
Thank you.

68
00:10:12,059 --> 00:10:14,059


69
00:10:14,864 --> 00:10:18,908
The Japanese are stalling, Henry.You know that.

70
00:10:20,803 --> 00:10:23,566
When Nomura took over as ambassador...

71
00:10:24,443 --> 00:10:26,039
... l had some hopes of settling our differences.

72
00:10:27,447 --> 00:10:30,803
But our meetings so far have been unproductive.

73
00:10:31,084 --> 00:10:34,639
He brings me proposals,I offer compromises.

74
00:10:35,756 --> 00:10:37,485
He brings me counterproposals, and so on.

75
00:10:37,791 --> 00:10:43,236
I tell you, Henry, Nomura was sent here to buy time.

76
00:10:45,537 --> 00:10:46,937
That's what he's doing, at our expense.

77
00:10:47,730 --> 00:10:50,960
The president believes him to be...

78
00:10:51,158 --> 00:10:54,458
...a man we can trust and deal with.

79
00:10:57,305 --> 00:11:00,170
Mr. Ambassador, we meet again.

80
00:11:00,208 --> 00:11:03,035
It is always a pleasure.

81
00:11:03,178 --> 00:11:06,770
I assume you know Mr. Stimson, the head of our War Department.

82
00:11:07,082 --> 00:11:09,004
Oh, yes, of course.

83
00:11:09,284 --> 00:11:10,810
Mr. Ambassador.

84
00:11:11,753 --> 00:11:17,449
I do hope, Mr. Stimson your presence here does not indicate anything ominous.

85
00:11:17,579 --> 00:11:18,482
Of course not, Mr. Nomura.

86
00:11:18,770 --> 00:11:21,162
Mr. Nomura, won't you please sit down?

87
00:11:21,372 --> 00:11:22,914
Thank you.

88
00:11:28,037 --> 00:11:31,125
Well, since our last talk a week ago...

89
00:11:31,974 --> 00:11:39,414
... l have received certain shall we say questions from my government...

90
00:11:40,081 --> 00:11:43,612
...to put to you to clarify certain matters.

91
00:11:51,813 --> 00:11:54,513


92
00:12:04,373 --> 00:12:05,271
Good morning, colonel.

93
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:11,738
There it is.

94
00:12:14,917 --> 00:12:19,612
This machine lets us intercept every word between Tokyo...

95
00:12:19,921 --> 00:12:21,749
...and all Japanese embassies.

96
00:12:22,925 --> 00:12:25,120
The coded material is fed into that machine.

97
00:12:27,364 --> 00:12:30,993
It goes round and round in there...

98
00:12:32,002 --> 00:12:35,028
...and comes out here, decoded in Japanese.

99
00:12:35,438 --> 00:12:37,633
All we have to do is translate it.

100
00:12:41,378 --> 00:12:42,840
We decode this quicker than the Japanese embassy...

101
00:12:42,879 --> 00:12:45,773
...right here in Washington.

102
00:12:45,871 --> 00:12:48,371


103
00:12:48,885 --> 00:12:51,149
No wonder you decided to call it "Operation Magic."

104
00:12:54,090 --> 00:12:56,623
- The latest intercept, sir. - Thank you.

105
00:13:02,098 --> 00:13:05,628
Things are getting a little hotter in the Pacific.

106
00:13:14,044 --> 00:13:16,342
As long as we're sharing this assignment...

107
00:13:18,447 --> 00:13:19,675
...take a look at this.

108
00:13:25,621 --> 00:13:27,509
Behold the 12 apostles.

109
00:13:28,390 --> 00:13:31,450
The chosen few are authorized to see the magic intercepts.

110
00:13:32,628 --> 00:13:36,155
Hap Arnold, Chief of the Air Corps, isn't on the list.

111
00:13:36,599 --> 00:13:37,429
No,

112
00:13:38,334 --> 00:13:40,529
and not one of our overseas commanders.

113
00:14:02,258 --> 00:14:03,850
fire

114
00:14:23,212 --> 00:14:24,372
Excellent!

115
00:14:31,654 --> 00:14:34,316
Who is in command of those torpedo planes?

116
00:14:34,824 --> 00:14:37,952
Lt. Commander Fuchida, sir, from the carrier Akagi.

117
00:14:38,661 --> 00:14:40,993
Send him this message from me.

118
00:14:41,397 --> 00:14:43,820
"Congratulations on brilliant torpedo attack."

119
00:15:04,987 --> 00:15:08,411
lf we are forced into a war with America...

120
00:15:09,358 --> 00:15:11,087
...Japan's only hope...

121
00:15:11,360 --> 00:15:14,989
...is to annihilate the American Pacific fleet at the outset.

122
00:15:17,766 --> 00:15:21,166
I wonder if we could use torpedo planes at Pearl Harbor?

123
00:15:25,867 --> 00:15:28,367
Pearl Harbor

124
00:15:32,847 --> 00:15:34,212
Stand by.

125
00:15:37,518 --> 00:15:38,450
Execute.

126
00:15:56,538 --> 00:15:58,957
Look at that entrance to the harbor.

127
00:15:59,373 --> 00:16:05,300
Sink one good-sized ship in the channel and you've bottled up our whole fleet.

128
00:16:05,546 --> 00:16:08,310
You know as well as l do,

129
00:16:08,549 --> 00:16:10,244
this harbor is a mousetrap.

130
00:16:11,385 --> 00:16:13,717
Fleet should have stayed in San Diego where it belongs.

131
00:16:16,057 --> 00:16:18,946
I made the mistake to point that out to Roosevelt.

132
00:16:18,978 --> 00:16:21,983
We're expected to obey orders.

133
00:16:22,897 --> 00:16:25,729
We're also expected to exercise our own good judgment.

134
00:16:27,401 --> 00:16:28,800
I didn't ask for the job.

135
00:16:29,989 --> 00:16:34,734
Sorry, Kim, but this was my command, and it's become habit...

136
00:16:35,006 --> 00:16:37,573
...to worry about the security of the fleet.

137
00:16:38,497 --> 00:16:42,140
The British, flying some old biplanes...

138
00:16:42,250 --> 00:16:45,643
...torpedoed and sank three ltalian battleships at Taranto.

139
00:16:46,087 --> 00:16:47,884
Harbor very much like this one.

140
00:16:48,389 --> 00:16:49,185
yeah

141
00:16:49,591 --> 00:16:53,594
I share your concern, but CNO doesn't think it can happen here.

142
00:16:53,846 --> 00:16:55,254
Why not?

143
00:16:55,796 --> 00:17:01,393
A torpedo dropped from a plane plunges...to a depth of 75 feet or more before it levels off.

144
00:17:01,802 --> 00:17:03,929
I know, and Pearl is only 40 feet deep.

145
00:17:06,374 --> 00:17:07,466
I'm still worried, Kim.

146
00:17:16,617 --> 00:17:21,845
Frankly, sir, l was stunned when l heard of your proposal.

147
00:17:22,723 --> 00:17:24,554
You think the plan is reckless?

148
00:17:25,210 --> 00:17:28,788
You suggest using torpedo planes against the American Fleet...

149
00:17:29,130 --> 00:17:31,291
...but Pearl Harbor is too shallow for that.

150
00:17:31,499 --> 00:17:33,694
Taranto is also a shallow harbor...

151
00:17:34,268 --> 00:17:36,429
...but the British torpedoed ...

152
00:17:36,504 --> 00:17:38,893
and sank three ltalian battleships there.

153
00:17:40,007 --> 00:17:42,601
I know as well as you do that my plan is a gamble.

154
00:17:42,677 --> 00:17:44,133
And it's risky,

155
00:17:44,946 --> 00:17:48,870
but we have no choice.

156
00:17:49,417 --> 00:17:53,246
What l need immediately is a plan for such an attack.

157
00:17:54,355 --> 00:17:55,617
I understand

158
00:17:55,690 --> 00:17:58,488
Then we should consult with Genda...

159
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:00,522
Genda?

160
00:18:00,962 --> 00:18:01,951
...the new Air Staff Officer on the Akagi,

161
00:18:02,298 --> 00:18:04,824
a superb strategist.

162
00:18:05,166 --> 00:18:07,999
Yes, l remember Genda. We'll talk to him.

163
00:18:20,903 --> 00:18:24,803


164
00:18:42,904 --> 00:18:44,865
Glad to see you, Genda.

165
00:18:45,406 --> 00:18:47,397
So this is the new Zero?

166
00:18:48,209 --> 00:18:50,404
Type 21, with folding wings.

167
00:18:53,247 --> 00:18:55,805
This means we can carry more fighters now.

168
00:18:56,751 --> 00:19:00,679
This Zero is fast, maneuverable and has a long cruising range.

169
00:19:01,823 --> 00:19:03,785
Better than the Messerschmitt or Spitfire?

170
00:19:04,175 --> 00:19:07,493
Definitely. I've seen both in combat over London.

171
00:19:07,895 --> 00:19:09,480
You outrank me, so it must be true.

172
00:19:12,433 --> 00:19:14,697
Now that you're Staff Officer here,

173
00:19:14,869 --> 00:19:16,962
things will be tough.

174
00:19:18,739 --> 00:19:21,663
You don't have to worry, you won't be here.

175
00:19:21,876 --> 00:19:24,572
You're going to the Third Fleet with a promotion.

176
00:19:26,580 --> 00:19:29,276
The Commander-in-Chief must think you're good!

177
00:19:30,618 --> 00:19:33,143
Of course he does! And I've got proof!

178
00:19:33,754 --> 00:19:36,552
Here is his telegram. Want to read it?

179
00:19:58,553 --> 00:20:02,753


180
00:20:04,285 --> 00:20:05,809
Ten-hut!

181
00:20:16,897 --> 00:20:20,927
Do the planes have to be parked like that?  Way at the edge of the field.

182
00:20:21,402 --> 00:20:23,199
Standard dispersal procedure, general.

183
00:20:23,571 --> 00:20:24,833
ln case of enemy air attack.

184
00:20:26,674 --> 00:20:29,268
There are 130,000 Japanese on this island.

185
00:20:29,977 --> 00:20:31,842
Our main problem is sabotage.

186
00:20:33,814 --> 00:20:36,180
lt'd be too easy for enemy agents to sneak in at night...

187
00:20:36,417 --> 00:20:39,750
...and blow up every one of them if they're left out there.

188
00:20:40,821 --> 00:20:42,709
Make a note, Fielder, we'll have to make changes.

189
00:20:42,890 --> 00:20:44,414
Yes Sir

190
00:20:44,592 --> 00:20:45,889
Ten-hut.

191
00:20:51,632 --> 00:20:54,190
- Yes? - Admiral Halsey's here to see you.

192
00:20:54,335 --> 00:20:55,290
Send him in, please.

193
00:20:58,548 --> 00:21:03,552
Blast me, break me, court-martial me, draw and quarter me...

194
00:21:03,878 --> 00:21:07,043
...if you think they're gonna send my ships...

195
00:21:07,181 --> 00:21:09,373
...on convoy duty in the Atlantic.

196
00:21:09,850 --> 00:21:12,316
Kim, l think they've gone nuts in Washington.

197
00:21:12,453 --> 00:21:14,842
How will l fight a task force if they send...

198
00:21:15,089 --> 00:21:16,775
...my ships to the Atlantic?

199
00:21:16,775 --> 00:21:20,444
That damn ocean is a swimming hole compared to the Pacific.

200
00:21:20,861 --> 00:21:22,952
What are we, a fighting fleet, or are these toy boats out here...

201
00:21:23,097 --> 00:21:26,828
...so the Japs can buy them at Christmas?

202
00:21:27,635 --> 00:21:30,024
All right, Bill, now ease it off.

203
00:21:30,071 --> 00:21:31,565
It's not just you.

204
00:21:32,332 --> 00:21:34,966
They asked for some of our tankers too.

205
00:21:35,576 --> 00:21:40,589
How do they expect to feed these wagons...parked out here on this land-locked duck pond?

206
00:21:40,981 --> 00:21:43,472
You're still planning on rotating half of them at sea?

207
00:21:43,885 --> 00:21:45,450
I was.

208
00:21:45,778 --> 00:21:49,640
Look, Kim, you've got to make them understand what's going on out here.

209
00:21:53,427 --> 00:21:55,452
I'm gonna do everything l can, Bill.

210
00:21:56,897 --> 00:21:58,660
Even go to the president.

211
00:22:01,535 --> 00:22:07,366
By God, l knew there was at least one man...in this man's Navy who hadn't gone nuts.

212
00:22:46,480 --> 00:22:48,368
"Gandhi" is still in hiding, sir.

213
00:22:49,917 --> 00:22:54,411
A strange man, he works in his cabin like a hermit.

214
00:22:55,289 --> 00:22:57,586
But he should be here.

215
00:22:58,592 --> 00:23:01,891
Watanabe, go and ask him to join us.

216
00:23:03,831 --> 00:23:08,189
When "Gandhi" concentrates on a plan, he is lost to this world.

217
00:23:11,001 --> 00:23:14,401


218
00:23:15,776 --> 00:23:19,633
Please don't bother me! This is important...

219
00:23:20,381 --> 00:23:21,609
...so I'm not going.

220
00:23:24,285 --> 00:23:27,243
Genda's plan for attacking Pearl Harbor...

221
00:23:27,355 --> 00:23:32,850
...is foolproof. It's brilliant!

222
00:23:34,228 --> 00:23:37,356
He stresses the importance of combat aircraft.

223
00:23:41,035 --> 00:23:50,296
Just think of it. We use six aircraft carriers...

224
00:23:51,304 --> 00:23:53,211
...torpedo planes...

225
00:23:55,049 --> 00:23:57,005
...high-level bombers, dive bombers.

226
00:23:57,718 --> 00:23:59,743
Zero fighters for cover...

227
00:24:00,321 --> 00:24:05,679
...go by the northern route, use the new torpedoes...

228
00:24:11,031 --> 00:24:14,429
...we attack on a weekend.

229
00:24:16,121 --> 00:24:19,198
Genda has thought of everything...

230
00:24:20,975 --> 00:24:23,500
...refueling...

231
00:24:25,813 --> 00:24:29,704
...the weather....

232
00:24:30,469 --> 00:24:34,408
And we go on to say, "lt should be noted that Japan...

233
00:24:34,622 --> 00:24:38,046
...has never preceded hostile action by a declaration of war.

234
00:24:38,685 --> 00:24:41,479
We have concluded it possible that a fast-rated...

235
00:24:41,688 --> 00:24:45,733
...Japanese carrier force may arrive in Hawaii with no prior warning...

236
00:24:45,901 --> 00:24:47,902
...from our intelligence service.

237
00:24:48,153 --> 00:24:51,405
The most favorable time to the enemy would be dawn.

238
00:24:51,573 --> 00:24:54,825
He probably would employ a maximum of six carriers...

239
00:24:55,076 --> 00:24:56,785
...strike on a weekend.

240
00:24:57,078 --> 00:24:59,709
- We recommend that the Air Corps--" - l read it.

241
00:25:00,981 --> 00:25:01,777
Yes, sir.

242
00:25:03,084 --> 00:25:08,441
I appreciate the work that you and General Martin have put in.

243
00:25:09,023 --> 00:25:12,379
These reports are very useful to General Short and myself.

244
00:25:13,678 --> 00:25:17,522
General Martin, you don't pull any punches, do you?

245
00:25:20,668 --> 00:25:25,368
"We recommend that the Air Corps maintain a thorough 360-degree 

246
00:25:25,368 --> 00:25:30,069
search of the Hawaiian area during daylight.

247
00:25:31,512 --> 00:25:35,869
This will require a force of 180 B-1 7 airplanes."

248
00:25:36,150 --> 00:25:40,680
We can't search the sea approaches unless we have the planes, sir.

249
00:25:40,888 --> 00:25:42,879
One hundred and eighty B-1 7s?

250
00:25:45,526 --> 00:25:48,490
For God's sakes, that's more than the number existing in the States.

251
00:25:48,529 --> 00:25:54,057
It looks fine on paper, but that's not a paper fleet out there.

252
00:25:55,936 --> 00:25:57,892
Squadron from the Enterprise.

253
00:25:58,189 --> 00:26:00,808
Bill Halsey's working the tails off his men.

254
00:26:03,061 --> 00:26:05,238
Wish we had more like him.

255
00:26:06,847 --> 00:26:10,146
Makes the most of what he's got.

256
00:26:10,276 --> 00:26:12,440
Doesn't keep asking for the moon.

257
00:26:28,068 --> 00:26:31,765
Well, not one bomb anywhere near the target for the past hour.

258
00:26:33,941 --> 00:26:37,297
Your pilots can see it, l suppose.

259
00:26:38,145 --> 00:26:41,243
- Who's next? - It's Anderson, sir.

260
00:26:48,389 --> 00:26:49,754
Now, that's more like it.

261
00:26:50,691 --> 00:26:53,986
- Maybe your boys finally get it. - l hope so, sir.

262
00:26:55,896 --> 00:26:58,091
Who's next?

263
00:26:58,399 --> 00:26:59,923
Lieutenant Dickenson.

264
00:27:06,407 --> 00:27:07,897
Tell Lieutenant Dickenson for me...

265
00:27:08,108 --> 00:27:11,703
...he couldn't hit a bull in the butt with a bass fiddle.

266
00:27:11,912 --> 00:27:12,776
