Sir, a message!

624
00:55:29,190 --> 00:55:30,817
Read

625
00:55:31,058 --> 00:55:35,324
"From Admiral Yamamoto, Commander-in-Chief, Combined Fleet...

626
00:55:35,963 --> 00:55:39,490
...to Admiral Nagumo, Third Fleet...

627
00:55:39,967 --> 00:55:42,458
...climb Mount Niitaka."

628
00:55:45,573 --> 00:55:49,168
Hostilities will begin on December 7th...

629
00:55:52,613 --> 00:55:55,070
...exactly as scheduled.

630
00:56:02,523 --> 00:56:04,115
Read this back to me.

631
00:56:09,163 --> 00:56:12,087
"Japanese future action unpredictable.

632
00:56:12,333 --> 00:56:15,427
But hostile action possible at any moment.

633
00:56:15,603 --> 00:56:18,834
lf hostilities cannot be avoided...

634
00:56:19,039 --> 00:56:22,668
...the United States desires that Japan commit the first overt act."

635
00:56:22,877 --> 00:56:25,366
Read that again.

636
00:56:27,848 --> 00:56:30,737
"lf hostilities cannot be avoided, the United States desires...

637
00:56:30,918 --> 00:56:36,919
...that Japan commit the first overt act.

638
00:56:38,526 --> 00:56:42,682
This shouldn't be construed as restricting you...

639
00:56:42,925 --> 00:56:45,720
...to a course of action jeopardizing your defense.

640
00:56:46,233 --> 00:56:48,565
Prior to hostile Japanese action...

641
00:56:49,036 --> 00:56:52,631
...you are directed to undertake reconnaissance...

642
00:56:52,957 --> 00:56:55,313
...and other measures as you deem necessary.

643
00:56:55,443 --> 00:57:00,073
These measures should be carried out so as not to alarm the civil population...

644
00:57:00,414 --> 00:57:02,177
...or disclose intent.

645
00:57:02,383 --> 00:57:04,214
By order of General George C. Marshall."

646
00:57:05,386 --> 00:57:09,618
"Not to alarm the civil population."

647
00:57:09,890 --> 00:57:11,687
What do you make of it?

648
00:57:12,726 --> 00:57:17,186
Well, if you ask me, sir,

649
00:57:17,398 --> 00:57:19,195
it's double talk.

650
00:57:20,367 --> 00:57:22,892
But the chief of staff doesn't go in for double talk.

651
00:57:23,737 --> 00:57:27,095
- We're going on alert. - Again?

652
00:57:27,241 --> 00:57:30,199
But the men are confused. So many alerts.

653
00:57:30,411 --> 00:57:32,876
- Damn it, unconfuse them. - Yes, sir.

654
00:57:35,549 --> 00:57:38,946
"Japanese forces may attack the Philippines...

655
00:57:38,973 --> 00:57:41,609
...Thailand, the Kra Peninsula and Borneo.

656
00:57:42,490 --> 00:57:45,152
This dispatch is to be considered a war warning."

657
00:57:49,763 --> 00:57:51,060
Well, there it is, gentlemen.

658
00:57:53,234 --> 00:57:55,657
You now have as much information as l do.

659
00:57:56,904 --> 00:57:58,929
That's the second warning in three days.

660
00:57:59,406 --> 00:58:04,529
"Japanese forces may attack the Philippines...Thailand, the Kra Peninsula and Borneo."

661
00:58:04,676 --> 00:58:05,601
They don't mention us.

662
00:58:05,912 --> 00:58:09,070
That's correct. l think it should be considered significant.

663
00:58:10,951 --> 00:58:15,935
Well, gentlemen... we have a job to do.

664
00:58:15,990 --> 00:58:20,086
Washington wants us to send a squadron of fighters to Midway.

665
00:58:20,461 --> 00:58:22,588
And another squadron to Wake.

666
00:58:23,731 --> 00:58:25,494
When can you sail?

667
00:58:26,433 --> 00:58:30,062
Well, the Enterprise can sail tomorrow morning.

668
00:58:31,539 --> 00:58:35,828
I'll need a day or two. We're just completing repairs on the Lexington.

669
00:58:36,944 --> 00:58:38,832
Hurry things along, John.

670
00:58:39,046 --> 00:58:40,843
I want you out there to probe.

671
00:58:41,015 --> 00:58:43,711
I want planes up in the air morning and afternoon.

672
00:58:43,951 --> 00:58:47,512
I want a report on any sign of hostile ships.

673
00:58:47,721 --> 00:58:48,813
Understood.

674
00:58:48,989 --> 00:58:50,547
Do you want battleships along?

675
00:58:50,758 --> 00:58:52,589
Hell, no. They're too slow.

676
00:58:52,793 --> 00:58:54,784
lf we're gonna probe, let's probe.

677
00:58:54,962 --> 00:58:57,055
We don't want anything holding us up.

678
00:58:57,331 --> 00:58:58,389
You're right, but I'm not ready to commit them myself.

679
00:58:58,599 --> 00:59:03,263
Not until l know when and where.

680
00:59:03,470 --> 00:59:06,428
Do you plan to keep half the fleet at sea while the carriers are gone?

681
00:59:06,640 --> 00:59:08,437
No, it's too risky.

682
00:59:08,676 --> 00:59:12,066
I'll have to keep the fleet here at Pearl while you're away.

683
00:59:12,346 --> 00:59:15,543
Get out. Get back as soon as you can.

684
00:59:15,749 --> 00:59:19,014
I don't like the idea of having my battleships without air cover.

685
00:59:20,287 --> 00:59:23,845
- Let's get going. - Yes, sir.

686
00:59:25,088 --> 00:59:26,506
Admiral.

687
00:59:32,800 --> 00:59:33,994
Kim.

688
00:59:35,169 --> 00:59:36,864
Level with me.

689
00:59:38,105 --> 00:59:40,801
I want a clear directive.

690
00:59:41,175 --> 00:59:42,608
lf l run into a Jap ship,

691
00:59:42,843 --> 00:59:43,832
what action do l take?

692
00:59:47,014 --> 00:59:50,040
Use your common sense.

693
00:59:52,353 --> 00:59:55,311
That's the best damn order l ever had.

694
00:59:58,525 --> 01:00:02,052
lf l see so much as a sampan there...

695
